AnimationPlayer

AnimationPlayer plays and queues handmade animations

With the AnimationPlayer node, you can create handcrafted animations.

When you create or select an AnimationPlayer node, a new editor appears in the bottom panel. It allows you to create and edit animations.

In Godot, you can animate any property you see in the Inspector. When an animation plays, it directly changes properties from one value to another over time.

An AnimationPlayer is the best tool to control lots of values changing at the same time. You can use it to animate characters, the environment, create cut-scenes, and even call functions and trigger events!

In this guide, you will learn how to:

  • Set up an AnimationPlayer and use its key methods and signals.
  • Create an animation to fade out a scene and respawn.
  • Call functions within an animation.
  • Create a queue of animations for an attack pattern.
  • Make a simple 3D gun reload animation.
  • Highlight 3D objects.

Weâ€™ll focus on the code-side of things here. To learn to use the animation editor, please watch this free intro to animation tutorial:

AnimationPlayerâ€™s key features

Godotâ€™s AnimationPlayer packs many features. Below, we look at a few important ones to get you started using the node in your projects.

A key feature is that it can animate nearly any property of any node, including those you define in scripts. Want to animate a monsterâ€™s movement speed during an animation? You can!

You can also call any function in animations. This feature replaces â€œanimation eventsâ€ as seen in some other game engines. You can use it to emit signals, kill an object, and much more.

Starting and stopping animations

An animation player has three main functions for playback:

  • play() takes the name of the animation to play as a parameter. This name gets stored in the current animation property for other functions to use. If you donâ€™t pass in a name, whatever animation is currently assigned resumes.

  • stop() stops the current animation and has an optional reset parameter. stop(true) seeks to the start of the current animation after stopping.

  • is_playing() returns a true or false value saying if an animation is currently playing.

Playback speed and reversing animations

The AnimationPlayer has a playback_speed variable which determines how quickly animations play.

playback_speed defaults to 1.0, but increasing it to 2.0 makes it play twice as fast.

The function play_backwards(), as the name suggests, plays the animation from the end and to the start. Under the hood, it plays the animation with a playback_speed of -1.0.

This is great for reusing animations, like fading in and out with one animation or animating a lever going one way or the other.

Note: The animation_finished signal emits when playing forward and backward. This can make it hard to distinguish between fading in and out this way in code.

Autoplay and looping

You can set an animation to play when the scene starts automatically. To do so, click the Autoplay On Load button in the animation bottom panel.

This is great for reducing unnecessary code. As a result, you rarely need to call AnimationPlayer.play() in a _ready() function.

Autoplay combines well with looping animations. Without code, you can have an animation play automatically and continuously.

For example, a coin spinning, a light flickering, or trees blowing in the wind. Note: the animation_finished signal doesnâ€™t emit for looping animations because they never end.

Easings and smooth animations

By default, animated properties change linearly. This kind of motion is rare in the real world, so it often looks unnatural.

Animation keyframes have an editable easing curve to control our animationâ€™s spacing (how the values change over time).

This lets us give our motion acceleration and deceleration.

When you click a keyframe and select it, the Inspector shows its properties. There, the Easing property displays as an interactive curve. Click and drag it to change the transition from this keyframe to the next one.

Alternatively, you can right-click to select an easing preset.

Lastly, you can double-click the curve to edit its numeric value.

A value less than 1.0 approaches the following key quickly then slow down. An easing of more than 1.0 approaches the next key slowly then speed up.

Easings appear with property animation tracks. Instead, you can opt for a more flexible Bezier Curve Track.

Bezier curves give you fine-grained control over your animation transitions. To create such a track, click Add Track -> Bezier Curve Track.

This shows the curve of values changing over time on the track itself for more precise control.

Queuing animations

You can queue as many animations as you wish to play once the current animation finishes, and only one animation_finished signal emits at the very end of the whole sequence.

To add animations to the queue, call the queue() function alongside the animationâ€™s name. You can remove every animation from the queue with the clear_queue() function.

Using sounds

The AnimationPlayer makes timing playing sounds a breeze. The audio playback track shows you the audio waveform in real-time.

This is particularly helpful to see when the sound finishes and when itâ€™s loudest.

Unfortunately, audio streams do not play well with the play_backwards function. The audio plays the same way regardless of the playback speed.

How to use an AnimationPlayer in practice

Creating a fade and respawn animation

To seamlessly respawn a player character, you can use a ColorRect to fade the whole screen to a solid color. This lets you move objects back to their starting location without the player seeing them.

Start by adding a CanvasLayer to your scene with a ColorRect filling the screen.

Note that by default, a ColorRect consumes mouse input, even if itâ€™s transparent. If you use it to fade the screen, be sure to set its Mouse -> Filter to Ignore to prevent that.

Add an AnimationPlayer and create a new animation. Set a keyframe where the ColorRectâ€™s Color property is a fully transparent black at the start and another with an opaque black at the end.

Note that you want the keyframes to use the same RGB colors when fading in and out and only animate their alpha channel. Otherwise, you may get a result that looks off.

Play the animation by calling AnimationPlayer.play() with its name as a parameter.

You can do that in a function and pause its execution until the animation finishes by calling yield().

AnimationPlayer emits an animation_finished signal when its current animation or the animation queue ends.

The yield() function waits until the given node emits the given signal, so code execution resumes when our screen has faded out. Afterward, we can reload the scene to respawn the player.

onready var _animation_player := $AnimationPlayer


func _on_SelfDestructButton_pressed() -> void:
    # If the animation is already playing, the screen is already fading out, so
    # we avoid running the function a second time.
    if _animation_player.is_playing():
        return

    # We spawn some particles and pause the player.
    _blast_particles.restart()
    _explosion_particles.restart()
    _player.set_physics_process(false)

    _animation_player.play("fade_out")
    # Here, we wait for the animation to end.
    yield(_animation_player, "animation_finished")

    _player.set_physics_process(true)
    # This animation reloads and restarts the current scene, which works for a
    # simple respawn.
    _animation_player.play("fade_in")

At the moment, the scene fades out then immediately appears when the reload happens. We can make this smoother with another animation.

To fade in, create a new animation and change the ColorRect from black to transparent.

Then click the Autoplay On Load button to make the animation play at the start, and the scene then fades in automatically.

Alternatively, if your fade-in and out animations have the same duration, you can create a single animation and reverse it by calling AnimationPlayer.play_backwards().

Creating an explosion animation that triggers code

An AnimationPlayer can call functions during an animation with a Call Method Track.

You can use this to trigger particles, deal damage at a specific time, or queue_free() a node. This is a powerful feature that can let us remove lots of unnecessary code.

This opens the door to many possibilities, including:

  • Emitting particles at a playerâ€™s feet in a walking animation.
  • Dealing damage and spawning bullets at specific points in an attack animation.
  • Applying forces to rigid bodies.
  • Deleting nodes at the end of an animation.

Before creating an explosion, we need a bomb scene. You can create it with an Area2D and a CollisionShape2D as a child. We use the area to detect the objects to damage when the bomb explodes.

You can find an example of how to create an area to detect and damage targets in the Area2D guide.

Create a Particles2D node with One Shot enabled. You can use the ProcessMaterial to create an explosion effect. This process is beyond the scope of this tutorial: see the Particles2D guide for more information.

Now, add a script to the Bomb scene and make the explode() function we want our animation to call.

func explode() -> void:
    # Get all bodies in the explosions radius
    var bodies: Array = _area.get_overlapping_bodies()

    for body in bodies:
        if body.has_method("take_damage"):
            # You can add this take_damage function to whatever scenes you want
            # the explosion to damage.
            body.take_damage()

Add an AnimationPlayer to the Bomb scene and create an animation named â€œexplode.â€ Make this play automatically with the Autoplay On Load button.

You can add a Call Method Track with the Add Track button in the top-left of the Animation bottom panel.

Then, select the node you want to call a method on: in our case, itâ€™s the Bomb. You need to add one of these tracks for every node you want to call a function on.

Add a key in the Call Method Track to call the explode() function when you want to do damage.

We can use the same track to free the Bomb in the animation. Add another key at the end of the animation which calls queue_free() on the bomb to delete it.

You can add as many Call Method Track as you want. For instance, you can add one for the Particles2D and have a key call its restart() function.

As youâ€™ve seen, we can call both built-in functions like Node.queue_free() or Particles2D.restart(), and ones we define in a script like explode().

Creating an attack pattern with a queue

You can queue animations to play one after another.

This lets you separate long animations into manageable chunks that are easier to reuse.

With this, you can have an animation for a coin spawning followed by an idle animation of it spinning.

It also gives you convenient options like queuing a death animation to play after a character finished its â€œtake damageâ€ animation.

In this example, we animated a turret and designed attack patterns with its animations.

We repeat the turretâ€™s animations a set number of times. Then, once all the attacks have finished, queue the next set of attacks.

Create a turret scene with an AnimationPlayer and a sprite for the turret.

We created three animations. The first two rotate the turret and call a shoot() function.

The â€œburstâ€ animation shoots series of bullets towards the player.

The â€œsprayâ€ animation shoots many bullets in an arc.

These animations can rotate the turret sprite relative to a pivot.

You can point the root node of the turret at the player with the look_at() function. As the turret is a child of the root, it also rotates, but its rotation property wonâ€™t change.

As a result, our animation aims relative to where the player currently is.

onready var _player: Player = get_node_or_null(player_path)

func _process(_delta: float) -> void:
    if not _player:
        return
    look_at(_player.global_position)

Finally, we have a â€œcooldownâ€ animation that animates the turretâ€™s tint, using its modulate property.

We created a dictionary with the names of our animations and how many times they should repeat.

const ATTACK_PATTERN_REPETITIONS := {"cooldown": 2, "burst": 3, "spray": 1}

Now, we can create the function that queues our attacks.

onready var _pattern_animator := $Pivot/AnimationPattern

func queue_shooting_pattern() -> void:
    # Get the attack animation names from the dictionary.
    var animations: Array = ATTACK_PATTERN_REPETITIONS.keys()
    # Randomize the order of our list of attacks, so the item at the front will
    # be random.
    animations.shuffle()
    var first_key: String = animations.front()

    # Find out how many times our animation should repeat
    for _x in range(ATTACK_PATTERN_REPETITIONS[first_key]):
        # Queue the animation so it will repeat for each time it's called in the
        # loop.
        _pattern_animator.queue(first_key)

Connect the animation_finished signal and have it call queue_shooting_pattern(). This makes our turret fire continuously.

Note: the animation_finished signal only emits after all queued animations finished playing.

func _ready() -> void:
    randomize()
    _pattern_animator.connect("animation_finished", self, "_on_AnimationPattern_animation_finished")
    queue_shooting_pattern()

# We need this callback because the signal comes with an argument but our
# queue_shooting_pattern() function takes none.
func _on_AnimationPattern_animation_finished(_anim_name: String) -> void:
    queue_shooting_pattern()

Creating a gun reload animation in 3D

Navigating 3D space is significantly more complex than 2D space, but using the AnimationPlayer node can make your life easier.

We use an animation player to make a series of reload animations that you can combine depending on context.

We animate:

  • Firing the shotgun.
  • Spinning the gun to show itâ€™s reloading if weâ€™re out of ammo.
  • Pumping to load the next shell.

Making the animations play in this varying order is a breeze thanks to the queue function. Then the majority of our animation tracks can be 3D transform properties like Translation, Rotation, and Scale.

We need the script for queueing our animations. This script prepares the animations above and instances a projectile scene to fire from the weapon as the fire animation starts.

func shoot() -> void:
    if _animator.is_playing():
        return
    _animator.queue("Fire")
    if _current_ammo < 1:
        _animator.queue("Reload")
    _current_ammo = posmod(_current_ammo - 1, max_ammo)
    _animator.queue("Pump")
    for _index in 9:
        var pellet: RayCast = pellet_scene.instance()
        add_child(pellet)

Now we can focus on creating our animations. With 3D animations, itâ€™s important to create a RESET animation to automatically return our model to a sensible default.

We made our gun with few meshes. The only ones we animate are the root node and the pump mesh.

When creating an animation like this, a typical workflow is to move your nodes to the desired position in the viewport and click the keyframe buttons in the inspector for each property you want to update. Then you can move through the timeline to the next point you want to add a keyframe and repeat.

For the â€œFireâ€ animation, we restart some particles with a Call Method Track. We immediately move the gun back and out to the right before returning it to its starting position.

We rotate vertically 360 degrees for the â€œReloadâ€ animation to end up in our starting orientation and slightly outwards while moving out and to the back before returning to the starting position.

We also increased the scale to add a bit more elasticity to the animation.

Finally, the â€œPumpâ€ animation rotates the gun up and to the left, then at the peak of this angle, quickly moves the pump back before returning all the properties to their origins.

Highlighting a mesh in 3D

Giving feedback to the player about what objects they can interact with is incredibly important for your overall game feel in any genre. It can be vital to highlight interactive things like ammo in an FPS, units you can click on in an RTS, or enemies in a hack-and-slash game.

Most simple highlights have known start and end states, so an AnimationPlayer is an ideal tool for the job.

In 3D, when dealing with meshes, Godot has a few helpful options for creating nodes from a mesh. This includes collision shapes, but more helpful for us: an outline MeshInstance.

We can use a RayCast to make the mesh visible whenever the player views an object, using an AnimationPlayer to fade out the outline when the player stops looking directly at it.

Firstly, letâ€™s cover viewing an object with a RayCast. Our RayCast should be a child of our camera and cast in the same direction. We need to check the Enabled property so the RayCast can collide with the objects we want to highlight.

Now, we can create our interactive object: a RigidBody, with a MeshInstance and a CollisionShape.

With the MeshInstance selected, you can click the Mesh button in the middle at the top of the viewport, select Create Outline Mesh from the dropdown and click Create.

You now have a child MeshInstance that highlights the original without even writing a shader!

This new outline mesh needs a material for us to animate, so add a new SpatialMaterial in the Material property, and enable the Transparent and Unshaded properties. In the Albedo property menu, you can choose the color for your outline.

We can now create our animation to highlight the object. In an AnimationPlayer, we only need one animation that fades the materialâ€™s alpha channel out over a fraction of a second.

Add a keyframe with our outline color, then after a small amount of time (we chose 0.2 seconds), add a keyframe with its alpha value set to 0. We also set the easing for these two keyframes to In-Out by right-clicking on the easing field.

Every frame the player is looking at the object, we restart the animation. This approach avoids us needing to keep track of if the player has stopped looking at the object, as the moment the player stops, the animation can continue and fade out on its own.

Now for the code that plays the animation:

extends RigidBody
class_name Interactible3D

onready var _animator: AnimationPlayer = $AnimationPlayer
func highlight() -> void:
    _animator.play("Highlight")
    _animator.seek(0, true)

The seek() function call is essential as otherwise, the animation would continue from its playback position rather than restarting every time we call the function.

Finally, we can hook up our RayCast to call the highlight function. In the _process() function we get the RayCastâ€™s collider and check if itâ€™s an Interactible3D object. If so, call its highlight function.

onready var _raycast: RayCast = $TiltPivot/Camera/RayCast
onready var _pickup: RemoteTransform = $TiltPivot/Camera/Pickup


func _physics_process(delta: float) -> void:
    if _raycast.get_collider() is Interactible3D:
        _pickup.remote_path = _raycast.get_collider().get_path()
        _raycast.get_collider().highlight()

Your questions

How can I set an animation to a specific point

The seek() function lets you pass in a time, and the current animation skips to that point. Another optional boolean determines whether to update the items to this point or not.

When should I use an animation player

It can be difficult to choose between using a Tween and an AnimationPlayer. The AnimationPlayer does have a few key strengths.

Itâ€™s easier to animate lots of properties with an animation player than a tween. Itâ€™s also easier to tweak and see how playback looks in real-time. This is because you can test your animation in real-time without needing to launch the game. You also have greater control over how properties change with easings or lots of keys.

The biggest reason not to use an AnimationPlayer is if youâ€™re animating a value that can change. For example, animating motion towards the mouse. An AnimationPlayer canâ€™t figure out where the mouse is, so a tween is much better for this case. One option is to use an AnimationPlayer and a tween at the same time, you can even start the tween with the animation. This lets you handle complex animations and variable motion at the same time.

The AnimationPlayer can greatly reduce the amount of code you need, so itâ€™s best to use them when you can.

Resetting my scene after playing animations

Playing an animation directly changes the properties of nodes in your scene. When you save the scene, the animated properties get saved in their current state too.

This is part of the systemâ€™s power, as it allows you to save an animationâ€™s state for free in a game or plugin, but it is also a bit of a curse when working on your game.

To work around that, you can create an animation that resets your scene to its default values. We typically name it â€œSETUP.â€

This animation should have a duration of 0 seconds. You can set it to autoplay to ensure all your nodes are ready at runtime.

In this animation, you create one keyframe for every property your other animations affect.

Whenever you need to reset your sceneâ€™s state, change the current animation to â€œSETUP.â€

How to animate any value with an AnimationPlayer

An AnimationPlayer canâ€™t set some properties. For example, the properties of an audio bus or the engineâ€™s time_scale.

Thankfully, we can get around this with a script.

In this example, we export a property to animate the engineâ€™s time_scale, which allows us to slow time.

In a script, we export a variable to control the target property. Then, we use the setget keyword to define a setter function.

In this function, we update the property thatâ€™s not accessible to the AnimationPlayer.

## Wrapper around the engine's time scale. Allows us to slow time in the
## animation player.
export var time_scale := 1.0 setget set_time_scale


func set_time_scale(value: float) -> void:
    time_scale = value
    # Thanks to this setter function, we can access the engine's properties.
    Engine.time_scale = time_scale

Now, our AnimationPlayer can access and animate that nodeâ€™s time_scale, which, in turn, animates the engineâ€™s time scale.

Note: While you could call a method directly with a Call Method Track, unlike with a property, you wouldnâ€™t benefit from the interpolation.

Saving and loading animations

You can save an animation and load it in another AnimationPlayer for reuse.

To do so, in the Animation bottom panel:

  • Click Animation -> Save Asâ€¦.
  • Save the file in your project.

You can now use Animation -> Load in another AnimationPlayer to reuse the animation.

Itâ€™s worth noting that the animation uses relative paths and node names to animate. As a result, you need to have the same node paths and names in the scene you reuse the animation.

You can, however, easily change an animation trackâ€™s node and property path. You just have to click the property name in the Animation bottom panel.

The paths have the form Path/To/Node:path/to/property. Note the node path can be . (a single dot), which targets the AnimationPlayerâ€™s parent. And .. targets the AnimationPlayerâ€™s grandparent.

You can also duplicate and rename animations to copy them quickly.

Thereâ€™s also an option to copy and paste an animation in the Animation menu.

However, as an animation is a Godot Resource under the hood, animations you copy and paste point to the same Animation resource in memory. As a result, modifying one copy causes the other animation to change accordingly.

To avoid that, use the Animation -> Duplicate option instead.
